Open CV functions and what they do 

Var = cv2.imread("xx.jpg") -> reads image and stores in val
assert Var is not None, "file could not be read, check with os.path.exists()" -> file doesnt exist check

cv2.imwrite("xxx.jpg", Var) -> spits out image

cv2.imshow("xx", Var) -> opens image in a new tab
cv2.waitKey(0) -> stops ^ the img from immediately closing

cv2.VideoCapture(video_path / "xxx.mp4" / webcam number to acces)

SIZING AND CROP
cv2.rotate(image, flag(cv2.ROTATE_90_CLOCKWISE))
cv2.resize(imgname, (widht, length))
image_crop = image[xx:xx, xx:xx] -> not a function but to crop an interval

RELEASING MEMMORY
video.release() - > closes video and frees resources
cv.DestroyAllWindows() -> closes all video or image deslpalys that were opened with .imshow

COLOR SPACES

cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY) -> function convers image to gray scale from BGR
cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB) -> function convers image to RGB from BGR
cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2HSV) -> function convers image to HSV from BGR
https://docs.opencv.org/3.4/d8/d01/group__imgproc__color__conversions.html -> list of all

import os -> allows you to grab pictures and videos from a folder

BLUR
cv2.blur(imgname, (x,y)) -> Averaging blur
cv2.GaussianBlur(imgname, (x,y), z) -> more natural/soft blur?
cv2.medianBlur(imgname, x)  -> great for removing noise
video_path / image_path = os.path.join('.','foldername','filename')

THRESHOLDING -> Converts image into binary(0 and 1 / balck and white) image setting pixels above a chosen value to one color and below it to another.
cv.treshold(imgname,(threshold val),255,thresholdtype)
thresholdtypes -> cv2.THRESH_BINARY


EDGE DETECTORS
Sobel Derivatives:
Laplace Operator:
Canny Edge detector: cv2.Canny(img, value(100), value(200))
cv2.dilate(image, kernel) -> makes lines thicker
cv2.erode(image, kernel) -> shrinks / thins lines


Drawing:
cv2.line(img, (x,y)(starting point) , (x,y)(ending point), (r,g,b), thickness)
cv2.rectangle(img, (x,y)(top-left corner), (x,y)(bottom-right corner), (r,g,b), thickness)
cv2.circle(img, (x,y)(center), radius, (r,g,b), thickness)
cv2.putText(img, "text", (x,y)(bottom-left of text), font, fontScale, (r,g,b), thickness)


















